# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rego-opa-policy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] In computer security, an **access-control list** (**ACL**) is a list of permissions associated with a system resource (object or facility).
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] An ACL specifies which users or system processes are granted access to resources, as well as what operations are allowed on given resources.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Each entry in a typical ACL specifies a subject and an operation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Many kinds of operating systems implement ACLs or have a historical implementation; the first implementation of ACLs was in the filesystem of Multics in 1965.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] A filesystem ACL is a data structure (usually a table) containing entries that specify individual user or group rights to specific system objects such as programs, processes, or files.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] These entries are known as access-control entries (ACEs) in the Microsoft Windows NT, OpenVMS, and Unix-like operating systems such as Linux, macOS, and Solaris.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Each accessible object contains an identifier to its ACL.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] The privileges or permissions determine specific access rights, such as whether a user can read from, write to, or execute an object.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] In some implementations, an ACE can control whether or not a user, or group of users, may alter the ACL on an object.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] One of the first operating systems to provide filesystem ACLs was Multics.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] PRIMOS featured ACLs at least as early as 1984.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] In the 1990s the ACL and role-based access control (RBAC) models were extensively tested and used to administer file permissions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] POSIX 1003.1e/1003.2c working group made an effort to standardize ACLs, resulting in what is now known as "POSIX.1e ACL" or simply "POSIX ACL".
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] The POSIX.1e/POSIX.2c drafts were withdrawn in 1997 due to participants losing interest for funding the project and turning to more powerful alternatives such as NFSv4 ACLs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] As of December 2019, no live sources of the draft could be found on the Internet, but it can still be found in the Internet Archive.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Most of the Unix and Unix-like operating systems (e.g.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Linux since 2.5.46 or November 2002, FreeBSD, or Solaris) support POSIX.1e ACLs (not necessarily draft 17).
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] ACLs are usually stored in the extended attributes of a file on these systems.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are much more powerful than POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Unlike draft POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are defined by a published standard, as part of the Network File System.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are supported by many Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Examples include AIX, FreeBSD, Mac OS X beginning with version 10.4 ("Tiger"), or Solaris with ZFS filesystem, support NFSv4 ACLs, which are part of the NFSv4 standard.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] There are two experimental implementations of NFSv4 ACLs for Linux: NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext3 filesystem and the more recent Richacls, which brings NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext4 filesystem.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] As with POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are usually stored as extended attributes on Unix-like systems.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are organized nearly identically to the Windows NT ACLs used in NTFS.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] NFSv4.1 ACLs are a superset of both NT ACLs and POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Samba supports saving the NT ACLs of SMB-shared files in many ways, one of which is as NFSv4-encoded ACLs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Microsoft's Active Directory service implements an LDAP server that stores and disseminates configuration information about users and computers in a domain.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Active Directory extends the LDAP specification by adding the same type of access-control list mechanism as Windows NT uses for the NTFS filesystem.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Windows 2000 then extended the syntax for access-control entries such that they could not only grant or deny access to entire LDAP objects, but also to individual attributes within these objects.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] On some types of proprietary computer hardware (in particular, routers and switches), an access-control list provides rules that are applied to port numbers or IP addresses that are available on a host or other layer 3, each with a list of hosts and/or networks permitted to use the service.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Although it is additionally possible to configure access-control lists based on network domain names, this is a questionable idea because individual TCP, UDP, and ICMP headers do not contain domain names.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Consequently, the device enforcing the access-control list must separately resolve names to numeric addresses.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] This presents an additional attack surface for an attacker who is seeking to compromise security of the system which the access-control list is protecting.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Both individual servers and routers can have network ACLs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Access-control lists can generally be configured to control both inbound and outbound traffic, and in this context they are similar to firewalls.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Like firewalls, ACLs could be subject to security regulations and standards such as PCI DSS.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] ACL algorithms have been ported to SQL and to relational database systems.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Many "modern" (2000s and 2010s) SQL-based systems, like enterprise resource planning and content management systems, have used ACL models in their administration modules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] In 2024, schema-indexed ACL models emerged as a lightweight alternative to traditional JSON-based permission storage.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] One notable proposal introduced the idea of storing only the indexes of allowed operations, rather than full permission trees.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] This technique, later formalized as *SCode ACL*, allows compact encoding of access rights (e.g., `"0 2 5"`) based on a predefined flattened schema, making it particularly efficient for use in stateless systems such as JWT tokens or session cookies.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] The approach gained early traction in developer communities for its minimalism and performance, and has since been adopted in both small-scale and production-grade systems.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] The main alternative to the ACL model is the role-based access-control (RBAC) model.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] A "minimal RBAC model", *RBACm*, can be compared with an ACL mechanism, *ACLg*, where only groups are permitted as entries in the ACL.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] Barkley (1997) showed that *RBACm* and *ACLg* are equivalent.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] In modern SQL implementations, ACLs also manage groups and inheritance in a hierarchy of groups.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] So "modern ACLs" can express all that RBAC express and are notably powerful (compared to "old ACLs") in their ability to express access-control policy in terms of the way in which administrators view organizations.
[src:rego-opa-policy/access-control-list] For data interchange, and for "high-level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC is a method of implementing access control policies that is highly adaptable and can be customized using a wide range of attributes, making it suitable for use in distributed or rapidly changing environments.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The only limitations on the policies that can be implemented with ABAC are the capabilities of the computational language and the availability of relevant attributes.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC policy rules are generated as Boolean functions of the subject's attributes, the object's attributes, and the environment attributes.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Unlike role-based access control (RBAC), which defines roles that carry a specific set of privileges associated with them and to which subjects are assigned, ABAC can express complex rule sets that can evaluate many different attributes.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Through defining consistent subject and object attributes into security policies, ABAC eliminates the need for explicit authorizations to individuals’ subjects needed in a non-ABAC access method, reducing the complexity of managing access lists and groups.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute values can be set-valued or atomic-valued.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Set-valued attributes contain more than one atomic value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Atomic-valued attributes contain only one atomic value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Examples are *clearance* and *sensitivity*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be compared to static values or to one another, thus enabling relation-based access control.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control is sometimes referred to as **policy-based access control** (**PBAC**) or **claims-based access control** (**CBAC**), which is a Microsoft-specific term.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The key standards that implement ABAC are XACML and ALFA (XACML).
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP or Policy Decision Point is the brain of the architecture.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is the piece which evaluates incoming requests against policies it has been configured with.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The PIP or Policy Information Point bridges the PDP to external sources of attributes e.g.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be about anything and anyone.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies are statements that bring together attributes to express what can happen and is not allowed.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies in ABAC can be granting or denying policies.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies can also be local or global and can be written in a way that they override other policies.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] With ABAC you can have an unlimited number of policies that cater to many different scenarios and technologies.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Historically, access control models have included mandatory access control (MAC), discretionary access control (DAC), and more recently role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] These access control models are user-centric and do not take into account additional parameters such as resource information, the relationship between the user (the requesting entity) and the resource, and dynamic information, e.g. time of the day or user IP.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC tries to address this by defining access control based on attributes which describe the requesting entity (the user), the targeted object or resource, the desired action (view, edit, delete), and environmental or contextual information.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is why access control is said to be attribute-based.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] XACML, the eXtensible Access Control Markup Language, defines an architecture (shared with ALFA and NGAC), a policy language, and a request/response scheme.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] It does not handle attribute management (user attribute assignment, object attribute assignment, environment attribute assignment) which is left to traditional IAM tools, databases, and directories.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Companies, including every branch in the United States military, have started using ABAC.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] At a basic level, ABAC protects data with 'IF/THEN/AND' rules rather than assign data to users.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The US Department of Commerce has made this a mandatory practice and the adoption is spreading throughout several governmental and military agencies.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The concept of ABAC can be applied at any level of the technology stack and an enterprise infrastructure.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] For example, ABAC can be used at the firewall, server, application, database, and data layer.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The use of attributes bring additional context to evaluate the legitimacy of any request for access and inform the decision to grant or deny access.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] An important consideration when evaluating ABAC solutions is to understand its potential overhead on performance and its impact on the user experience.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] It is expected that the more granular the controls, the higher the overhead.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC can be used to apply attribute-based, fine-grained authorization to the API methods or functions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] For instance, a banking API may expose an `approveTransaction(transId)` method.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The API receives the call and authenticates the user.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP retrieves the ABAC policy and necessary attributes.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] If the decision is Permit, the underlying API business logic is called.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Otherwise the API returns an error or access denied.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] One of the key benefits to ABAC is that the authorization policies and attributes can be defined in a technology neutral way.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This means policies defined for APIs or databases can be reused in the application space.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] The same process and flow as the one described in the API section applies here too.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Security for databases has long been specific to the database vendors: Oracle VPD, IBM FGAC, and Microsoft RLS are all means to achieve fine-grained ABAC-like security.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Data security typically goes one step further than database security and applies control directly to the data element.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is often referred to as data-centric security.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] On traditional relational databases, ABAC policies can control access to data at the table, column, field, cell and sub-cell using logical controls with filtering conditions and masking based on attributes.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be data, user, session or tools based to deliver the greatest level of flexibility in dynamically granting/denying access to a specific data element.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] On big data, and distributed file systems such as Hadoop, ABAC applied at the data layer control access to folder, sub-folder, file, sub-file and other granular.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control can also be applied to Big Data systems like Hadoop.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] Policies similar to those used previously can be applied when retrieving data from data lakes.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] As of Windows Server 2012, Microsoft has implemented an ABAC approach to controlling access to files and folders.
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] This is achieved through dynamic access control (DAC) and Security Descriptor Definition Language (SDDL).
[src:rego-opa-policy/attribute-based-access-control] SDDL can be seen as an ABAC language as it uses metadata of the user (claims) and of the file/ folder to control access.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Authorization is closely related to access control, which is what enforces the authorization policy by deciding whether access requests to resources from (authenticated) consumers shall be approved (granted) or disapproved (rejected).
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Authorization should not be confused with authentication, which is the process of verifying someone's identity.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Hence, access control in computer systems and networks relies on access authorization specified during configuration.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Authorization is the responsibility of an authority, such as a department manager, within the application domain, but is often delegated to a custodian such as a system administrator.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Authorizations are expressed as access policies in some types of "policy definition application", e.g. in the form of an access control list or a capability, or a policy administration point e.g.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Broken authorization is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] "Anonymous consumers" or "guests", are consumers that have not been required to authenticate.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] On a distributed system, it is often desirable to grant access without requiring a unique identity.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Familiar examples of access tokens include keys, certificates and tickets: they grant access without proving identity.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] A widely used framework for authorizing applications is OAuth 2.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] It provides a standardized way for third-party applications to obtain limited access to a user's resources without exposing their credentials.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] In modern systems, a widely used model for authorization is role-based access control (RBAC) where authorization is defined by granting subjects one or more roles, and then checking that the resource being accessed has been assigned at least one of those roles.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] However, with the rise of social media, Relationship-based access control is gaining more prominence.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Even when access is controlled through a combination of authentication and access control lists, the problems of maintaining the authorization data is not trivial, and often represents as much administrative burden as managing authentication credentials.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] It is often necessary to change or remove a user's authorization: this is done by changing or deleting the corresponding access rules on the system.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] Using atomic authorization is an alternative to per-system authorization management, where a trusted third party securely distributes authorization information.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] In public policy, authorization is a feature of trusted systems used for security or social control.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] In banking, an authorization is a hold placed on a customer's account when a purchase is made using a debit card or credit card.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] In publishing, sometimes public lectures and other freely available texts are published without the approval of the author.
[src:rego-opa-policy/authorization] An example is the 2002 *'The Theory of Everything: The Origin and Fate of the Universe'*, which was collected from Stephen Hawking's lectures and published without his permission as per copyright law.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] A Datalog program consists of *facts*, which are statements that are held to be true, and *rules*, which say how to deduce new facts from known facts.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The names are written in lowercase because strings beginning with an uppercase letter stand for variables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The meaning of a program is defined to be the set of all of the facts that can be deduced using the initial facts and the rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] This query asks: *Who are all the X that xerces is an ancestor of?* For this example, it would return *brooke* and *damocles*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The non-recursive subset of Datalog is closely related to query languages for relational databases, such as SQL.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] More formally, non-recursive Datalog corresponds precisely to unions of conjunctive queries, or equivalently, negation-free relational algebra.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] A Datalog program consists of a list of *rules* (Horn clauses).
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Atoms are also referred to as **literals**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The atom to the left of the `:-` symbol is called the **head** of the rule; the atoms to the right are the **body**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Every Datalog program must satisfy the condition that every variable that appears in the head of a rule also appears in the body (this condition is sometimes called the **range restriction**).
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] There are two common conventions for variable names: capitalizing variables, or prefixing them with a question mark `?`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Note that under this definition, Datalog does *not* include negation nor aggregates; see § Extensions for more information about those constructs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Rules with empty bodies are called **facts**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The set of facts is called the **extensional database** or **EDB** of the Datalog program.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The set of tuples computed by evaluating the Datalog program is called the **intensional database** or **IDB**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] These are merely abbreviations (syntactic sugar); they have no impact on the semantics of the program.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] There are three widely-used approaches to the semantics of Datalog programs: model-theoretic, fixed-point, and proof-theoretic.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] These three approaches can be proven equivalent.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] An atom is called **ground** if none of its subterms are variables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Intuitively, each of the semantics define the meaning of a program to be the set of all ground atoms that can be deduced from the rules of the program, starting from the facts.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] A rule is called ground if all of its atoms (head and body) are ground.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] A rule *R*2 is a *ground instance* of another rule *R*1 if *R*2 is the result of a substitution of constants for all the variables in *R*1.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The *Herbrand base* of a Datalog program is the set of all ground atoms that can be made with the constants appearing in the program.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The **Herbrand model** of a Datalog program is the smallest subset of the Herbrand base such that, for each ground instance of each rule in the program, if the atoms in the body of the rule are in the set, then so is the head.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The model-theoretic semantics define the minimal Herbrand model to be the meaning of the program.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Let I be the power set of the Herbrand base of a program *P*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The *immediate consequence operator* for *P* is a map T from I to I that adds all of the new ground atoms that can be derived from the rules of the program in a single step.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The least-fixed-point semantics define the least fixed point of T to be the meaning of the program; this coincides with the minimal Herbrand model.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The fixpoint semantics suggest an algorithm for computing the minimal model: Start with the set of ground facts in the program, then repeatedly add consequences of the rules until a fixpoint is reached.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] This algorithm is called naïve evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The proof-theoretic semantics defines the meaning of a Datalog program to be the set of facts with corresponding *proof trees*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Intuitively, a proof tree shows how to derive a fact from the facts and rules of a program.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] One might be interested in knowing whether or not a particular ground atom appears in the minimal Herbrand model of a Datalog program, perhaps without caring much about the rest of the model.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] A top-down reading of the proof trees described above suggests an algorithm for computing the results of such *queries*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] This reading informs the SLD resolution algorithm, which forms the basis for the evaluation of Prolog.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] There are many different ways to evaluate a Datalog program, with different performance characteristics.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Bottom-up evaluation strategies start with the facts in the program and repeatedly apply the rules until either some goal or query is established, or until the complete minimal model of the program is produced.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Semi-naïve evaluation is a bottom-up evaluation strategy that can be asymptotically faster than naïve evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] In naïve evaluation, the same facts may be discovered over and over again, while semi-naïve evaluation avoids this repeated computation by only working with the new tuples generated in the previous iteration.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Naïve and semi-naïve evaluation both evaluate recursive Datalog rules by repeatedly applying them to a set of known facts until a fixed point is reached.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] In each iteration, rules are only run for "one step", i.e., non-recursively.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] As mentioned above, each non-recursive Datalog rule corresponds precisely to a conjunctive query.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Many such techniques are implemented in modern bottom-up Datalog engines such as Soufflé.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Some Datalog engines integrate SQL databases directly.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Bottom-up evaluation of Datalog is also amenable to parallelization.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] SLD resolution is sound and complete for Datalog programs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Top-down evaluation strategies begin with a *query* or *goal*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Bottom-up evaluation strategies can answer queries by computing the entire minimal model and matching the query against it, but this can be inefficient if the answer only depends on a small subset of the entire model.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The *magic sets* algorithm takes a Datalog program and a query, and produces a more efficient program that computes the same answer to the query while still using bottom-up evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] A variant of the magic sets algorithm has been shown to produce programs that, when evaluated using semi-naïve evaluation, are as efficient as top-down evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The decision problem formulation of Datalog evaluation is as follows: "Given a Datalog program P split into a set of facts (EDB) E and a set of rules R, and a ground atom A.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] With respect to data complexity, the decision problem for Datalog is P-complete (See Theorem 4.4 in ).
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] P-completeness for data complexity means that there exists a fixed Datalog query for which evaluation is P-complete.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The proof is based on *Datalog metainterpreter* for propositional logic programs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] With respect to program complexity, the decision problem is EXPTIME-complete.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] In particular, evaluating Datalog programs always terminates; Datalog is not Turing-complete.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Some extensions to Datalog do not preserve these complexity bounds.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Extensions implemented in some Datalog engines, such as algebraic data types, can even make the resulting language Turing-complete.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Several extensions have been made to Datalog, e.g., to support negation, aggregate functions, inequalities, to allow object-oriented programming, or to allow disjunctions as heads of clauses.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] These extensions have significant impacts on the language's semantics and on the implementation of a corresponding interpreter.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog is a syntactic subset of Prolog, disjunctive Datalog, answer set programming, DatalogZ, and constraint logic programming.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] When evaluated as an answer set program, a Datalog program yields a single answer set, which is exactly its minimal model.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Many implementations of Datalog extend Datalog with additional features; see § Datalog engines for more information.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog can be extended to support aggregate functions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Adding negation to Datalog complicates its semantics, leading to whole new languages and strategies for evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] For example, the language that results from adding negation with the stable model semantics is exactly answer set programming.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Stratified negation can be added to Datalog while retaining its model-theoretic and fixed-point semantics.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Unlike in Prolog, statements of a Datalog program can be stated in any order.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog does not have Prolog's cut operator.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] This makes Datalog a fully declarative language.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] This article deals primarily with Datalog without negation (see also Syntax and semantics of logic programming § Negation).
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] However, stratified negation is a common addition to Datalog; the following list contrasts Prolog with Datalog with stratified negation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog generalizes many other query languages.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] For instance, conjunctive queries and union of conjunctive queries can be expressed in Datalog.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog can also express regular path queries.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The **boundedness problem** for Datalog asks, given a Datalog program, whether it is **bounded**, i.e., the maximal recursion depth reached when evaluating the program on an input database can be bounded by some constant.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] In other words, this question asks whether the Datalog program could be rewritten as a nonrecursive Datalog program, or, equivalently, as a union of conjunctive queries.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Solving the boundedness problem on arbitrary Datalog programs is undecidable, but it can be made decidable by restricting to some fragments of Datalog.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Systems that implement languages inspired by Datalog, whether compilers, interpreters, libraries, or embedded DSLs, are referred to as **Datalog engines**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog engines often implement extensions of Datalog, extending it with additional data types, foreign function interfaces, or support for user-defined lattices.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Such extensions may allow for writing non-terminating or otherwise ill-defined programs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog is quite limited in its expressivity.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] It is not Turing-complete, and doesn't include basic data types such as integers or strings.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] This parsimony is appealing from a theoretical standpoint, but it means Datalog *per se* is rarely used as a programming language or knowledge representation language.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Most Datalog engines implement substantial extensions of Datalog.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] However, Datalog has a strong influence on such implementations, and many authors don't bother to distinguish them from Datalog as presented in this article.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Accordingly, the applications discussed in this section include applications of realistic implementations of Datalog-based languages.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog has been applied to problems in data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Google has developed an extension to Datalog for big data processing.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog has seen application in static program analysis.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The Soufflé dialect has been used to write pointer analyses for Java and a control-flow analysis for Scheme.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Datalog has been integrated with SMT solvers to make it easier to write certain static analyses.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The Flix dialect is also suited to writing static program analyses.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] Some widely used database systems include ideas and algorithms developed for Datalog.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] For example, the SQL:1999 standard includes recursive queries, and the Magic Sets algorithm (initially developed for the faster evaluation of Datalog queries) is implemented in IBM's DB2.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it became prominent as a separate area around 1977 when Hervé Gallaire and Jack Minker organized a workshop on logic and databases.
[src:rego-opa-policy/datalog] David Maier is credited with coining the term Datalog.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The most well known policy-based management architecture was specified jointly by the IETF and the DMTF.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] This consists of four main functional elements: the Policy Management Tool (PMT), Policy Repository, Policy Decision Point (PDP), and Policy Enforcement Point (PEP).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The PMT is used by an administrator to define or update the policies to be enforced in the managed network.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Resulting policies are stored in a repository in a form that must correspond to an information model so as to ensure interoperability across products from different vendors.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] When new policies have been added in the repository, or existing ones have been changed, the PMT issues the relevant PDP with notifications, which in turn interprets the policies and communicates them to the PEP.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The latter is a component that runs on a policy-aware node and can execute (enforce) the different policies.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The components of the architecture can communicate with each other using a variety of protocols.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The preferred choice for communicating policy decisions between a PDP and network devices (PEPs) is the Common Open Policy Service (COPS) or SNMP, and LDAP for the PMT/PDP–repository communication.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The simplest approach for policy specification is through a sequence of rules, in which each rule is the form of a simple condition-action pair.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The conditional part of the rule can be a simple or compound expression specified in either conjunctive or disjunctive normal form.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The action part of the rule can be a set of actions that must be executed when the conditions are true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The IETF does not define a specific language to express network policies but rather a generic object-oriented information model for representing policy information.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] This model is a generic one, specifying the structure of abstract policy classes by means of association, thus allowing vendors to implement their own set of conditions and actions to be used by the policy rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] As with any programmable system, a policy-driven one can suffer from inconsistencies incurred by contradicting rules governing its behaviour.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] These are known as policy conflicts and come about as a result of specification errors, omissions, or contradictory management operations and, in some cases, can have catastrophic effects on the operation of the managed system.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] They have also been described as being analogous to software bugs that occur when two or more policies are activated simultaneously enforcing contradictory management operations on the system.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Policy conflicts are broadly classified into domain-independent and application-specific, where the former, as the names suggest, are independent of the policy application, and the latter are bound by the constraints of the application domain.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Example application domains that have been considered in the literature include quality of service (QoS) in IP networks, distributed systems, firewall security, and call control in telecommunication networks.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] For example, conflicts can occur between policies for dynamically allocating resources and those setting quotas for users or classes of service.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] As such, automation should be a key aspect of dynamic analysis mechanisms so that the operational impact of a conflict can be kept to a minimum.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] To effectively use policies and drive the functionality of a managed system in a consistent manner, it is necessary to check that newly created policies do not conflict with each other or with policies already deployed in the system.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] To achieve this, detection processes utilise information regarding the conditions under which conflicts can arise to search policy spaces and identify policies that meet the conflict criteria.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Based on the types of conflicts identified in the literature and the different application domains in which they occur, research has concentrated in the development of mechanisms and techniques for their effective detection.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Popular approaches for the detection of conflicts have been based on: meta-policies (detection rules), policy relationships, applicability spaces, and information models.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Resolution is the latter part of policy analysis, which aims at handling detected inconsistencies, preferably in an automated manner, so that consistency among policies can be restored.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The process of resolving conflicts may involve retracting, suppressing, prioritising, or amending policies, and in some cases, enforcing a new policy altogether so that consistency among policy rules can be restored.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The methodology in doing so depends heavily on the type of policies involved and the domain in which conflicts occur.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Although human intervention is unavoidable in some situations, several research efforts focussed on techniques to automate the resolution process where possible.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Popular approaches for the resolution of conflicts have been based on: meta-policies (resolution rules), precedence, policy ordering, and conflict prevention.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The time-frame at which conflicts can be detected influences the analysis methodology and requirements for dealing with them.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Static conflicts are typically detected through analysis initiated manually by the system administrator; conflicts represent inconsistencies between policies and are typically resolved by amending the policies.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] In contrast, run-time conflicts must be detected by a process that monitors policy enforcement and detects inconsistent situations in the system’s execution.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Resolution must be achieved automatically, for example through enforcing resolution rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Lack of automation in the handling of run-time conflicts may have catastrophic consequences on the correct system operation, especially when managing QoS for delay sensitive applications.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Ideally, a policy-based management system should facilitate the definition of high-level administrative goals, which are easy for humans to express and understand, enable their translation into low-level policies and map them into commands that configure the managed devices accordingly.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] While the high-level goals reflect the business objectives of the network administrator, the low-level policies are responsible for device-level configurations.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Policy refinement is the process of transforming a high-level goal or abstract policy specification into low-level, concrete policies that can be enforced on the managed system.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] Several policy refinement approaches have been developed.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-based-management] The most notable ones are based on linear temporal logic, event calculus, and utility computing.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] OPA is purpose built for policy evaluation and uses its declarative language Rego to reason about structured data like API requests, infrastructure-as-code files, and configuration data.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego lets you express desired rules and decisions as code, and is designed to be easy to read and write while being optimized for fast policy evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego queries are assertions on data that can be used to define policies and make decisions about whether data violates the expected state of your system.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego was inspired by Datalog and extends it to support structured document models such as JSON.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Use Rego for defining policy that is easy to read and write.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego focuses on providing support for referencing nested documents and ensuring that queries are correct and unambiguous.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego is declarative so policy authors can focus on what queries should return rather than how queries should be executed.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] These queries are simpler and more concise than the equivalent in an imperative language.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Like other applications which support declarative query languages, OPA is able to optimize queries to improve performance.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] While reviewing the examples below, you might find it helpful to follow along using the online OPA playground.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The playground also allows sharing of examples via URL which can be helpful when asking questions on the OPA Slack.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In addition to these official resources, you may also be interested to check out the community learning materials and tools (6 projects).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This section introduces the main aspects of Rego.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The simplest rule is a single expression and is defined in terms of a scalar value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] You can compare two scalar or composite values, and when you do so you are checking if the two values are the same JSON value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] You can define a new concept using a rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For example, `v` below is true if the equality expression is true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Evaluating `v` returns `undefined` because the body of the rule never evaluates to `true`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] As a result, the document generated by the rule is not defined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Expressions that refer to undefined values are also undefined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] When evaluating rule bodies, OPA searches for variable bindings that make all of the expressions true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] There may be multiple sets of bindings that make the rule body true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If the **value** is not specified, it defaults to the boolean value of **true**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego references help you refer to nested documents.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The rule `prod_exists` asserts that there exists (at least) one document within `sites` where the `name` attribute equals `"prod"` using the `some` keyword.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The example above can be generalized with a rule that defines a set document instead of a boolean value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Here `site_names` is a set of all the site's name values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This section introduced the main aspects of Rego.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The rest of this document walks those new to Rego through other important aspects of the language.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Please review the Policy Reference for more detailed information about the Rego language.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Scalar values are the simplest type of term in Rego.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Scalar values can be strings, numbers, booleans, or null.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Documents can be defined solely in terms of scalar values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This is useful for defining constants that are referenced in multiple places.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego supports two different types of syntax for declaring strings.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The first is likely to be the most familiar: characters surrounded by double quotes.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In such strings, certain characters must be escaped to appear in the string, such as double quotes themselves, backslashes, etc.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] See the Policy Reference for a formal definition.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The other type of string declaration is a raw string declaration.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] These are made of characters surrounded by backticks (`), with the exception that raw strings may not contain backticks themselves.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Raw strings are what they sound like: escape sequences are not interpreted, but instead taken as the literal text inside the backticks.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For example, the raw string `hello\there` will be the text "hello\there", not "hello" and "here" separated by a tab.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Raw strings are particularly useful when constructing regular expressions for matching, as it eliminates the need to double escape special characters.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] A simple example is a regex to match a valid Rego variable.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] With a regular string, the regex is `"[a-zA-Z_]\\w*"`, but with raw strings, it becomes `[a-zA-Z_]\w*`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Runtime data can be incorporated into a string through string interpolation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] An interpolated string is composed of a template-string containing zero or more template-expressions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The `$` character identifies a template-string, and can be used with regular double-quoted strings (`$"hello"`), and backtick-quoted raw strings ($`hello`).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If a template-expression evaluates to an `undefined` value, the string `"<undefined>"` will be emitted instead.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This means string interpolation is safe to use in cases where a string result is always expected, but not all expression values are guaranteed at evaluation time.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Compared to the `sprintf` built-in function, not halting evaluation on `undefined` values make interpolated strings less error-prone, and is therefore the recommended alternative.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Left curly-brace escaping is also present for multi-line raw template-strings ($`\{}`), differentiating them from regular raw strings, where no escaping is recognized.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Composite values can also be defined in terms of variables or references.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] By defining composite values in terms of variables and references, rules can define abstractions over raw data and other rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Arrays are ordered collections of values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Arrays in Rego are zero-indexed, and may contain any value, including variable references.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Use arrays when order matters or when duplicate values are required.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Objects are unordered key-value collections.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In Rego, any value type can be used as an object key.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For example, the following assignment maps port **numbers** to a list of IP addresses (represented as strings).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] When Rego values are converted to JSON non-string object keys are marshalled as strings (because JSON does not support non-string object keys).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In addition to arrays and objects, Rego supports set values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Sets are unordered collections of unique values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Just like other composite values, sets can be defined in terms of scalars, variables, references, and other composite values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Set documents are collections of values without keys or order.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] OPA represents sets as arrays when serializing to JSON or other formats that do not support a set data type.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The important distinction between sets and arrays or objects is that sets are unkeyed while arrays and objects are keyed, i.e., you cannot refer to the index of an element within a set.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The built-in function `count({})` will still return `0` because `{}` is an empty object.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] However, since `{}` is not a set, it will not equal `set()` or something that evaluates to an empty set.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Variables are another kind of term in Rego.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] They appear in both the head and body of rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Variables appearing in the head of a rule can be thought of as input and output of the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Unlike many programming languages, where a variable is either an input or an output, in Rego a variable is simultaneously an input and an output.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If a query supplies a value for a variable, that variable is an input, and if the query does not supply a value for a variable, that variable is an output.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In this case, evaluating `q` with a variable `x` (which is not bound to a value) returns all of the values for `x` and all of the values for `q[x]`, which are always the same because `q` is a set.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Variables appearing in the head of a rule must also appear in a non-negated equality expression within the same rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This property ensures that if the rule is evaluated and all of the expressions evaluate to true for some set of variable bindings, the variable in the head of the rule will be defined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] References are used to access nested documents.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The simplest reference contains no variables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] References are typically written using the “dot-access” style.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Both forms are valid, however, the dot-access style is typically more readable.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Non-string keys such as numbers, booleans, and null.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Variable keys which are described later.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Composite keys which are described later.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The prefix of a reference identifies the root document for that reference.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] References can include variables as keys.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] References written this way are used to select a value from every element in a collection.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In the reference above, variables named `i` and `j` were used to iterate the collections.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If the variables are unused outside the reference, the convention is to replace them with an underscore (`_`) character.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The underscore is special because it cannot be referred to by other parts of the rule, e.g., the other side of the expression, another expression, etc.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The underscore can be thought of as a special iterator.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Each time an underscore is specified, a new iterator is instantiated.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Under the hood, OPA translates the `_` character to a unique variable name that does not conflict with variables and rules that are in scope.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] References can include composite values as keys if the key is being used to refer into a set.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Composite keys may not be used in refs for base data documents, they are only valid for references into virtual documents.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This is useful for checking for the presence of composite values within a set, or extracting all values within a set matching some pattern.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rules are often written in terms of multiple expressions that contain references to documents.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In the following example, the rule defines a set of arrays where each array contains an application name and a hostname of a server where the application is deployed.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Don't worry about understanding everything in this example right now.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The rule is joining the `apps` and `sites` documents implicitly.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In Rego (and other languages based on Datalog), joins are implicit.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Using a different key on the same array or object provides the equivalent of self-join in SQL.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Comprehensions provide a concise way of building composite values from sub-queries.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Like rules, comprehensions consist of a head and a body.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The body of a comprehension can be understood in exactly the same way as the body of a rule, that is, one or more expressions that must all be true in order for the overall body to be true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] When the body evaluates to true, the head of the comprehension is evaluated to produce an element in the result.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The body of a comprehension is able to refer to variables defined in the outer body.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In the above query, the second expression contains an array comprehension that refers to the `region` variable.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The region variable will be bound in the outer body.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Comprehensions are similar to the same constructs found in other languages like Python.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Comprehensions are often used to group elements by some key.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] A common use case for comprehensions is to assist in computing aggregate values (e.g., the number of containers running on a host).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Array comprehensions build array values out of sub-queries.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For example, the following rule defines an object where the keys are application names and the values are hostnames of servers where the application is deployed.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The hostnames of servers are represented as an array.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Object comprehensions build object values out of sub-queries.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Set comprehensions build a set values out of sub-queries.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rules define the content of virtual documents in OPA.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] When OPA evaluates a rule, OPA *generates* the content of the document that is defined by the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The sample code in this section make use of the data defined in References.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Querying the content of the new `hostnames` rule returns the same data as querying using the `sites[_].servers[_].hostname` reference directly.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This example introduces a few important aspects of Rego.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] First, the rule defines a set document where the contents are defined by the variable `name`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This rule defines a set document because the head only includes a key.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If the value had been set, this would create an object instead.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For a more formal definition of the rule syntax, see the Policy Reference document.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Second, the `sites[_].servers[_].hostname` fragment selects the `hostname` attribute from all the objects in the `servers` collection.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] From reading the fragment in isolation, it is not possible to tell whether the fragment refers to arrays or objects.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] It only indicates a collection of values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Third, the `name := sites[_].servers[_].hostname` expression binds the value of the `hostname` attribute to the variable `name`, which is also declared in the head of the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rules that define objects are very similar to rules that define sets.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Note that object rules have a key and a value in the head of the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The rule above defines an object that maps hostnames to app names.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The main difference between this rule and one which defines a set is the rule head: in addition to declaring a key, the rule head also declares a value for the document.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] A rule may be defined multiple times with the same name.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] When a rule is defined this way, the rule definition is called *incremental* because each definition is additive.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The document produced by incrementally defined rules is the union of the documents produced by each individual rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] An incrementally defined rule can be intuitively understood as `<rule-1> OR <rule-2> OR ...
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In addition to rules that *partially* define sets and objects, Rego also supports so-called *complete* definitions of any type of document.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rules provide a complete definition by omitting the key in the head.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego allows authors to omit the body of rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If the body is omitted, it defaults to true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Documents produced by rules with complete definitions can only have one value at a time.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If evaluation produces multiple values for the same document, an error will be returned.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] OPA returns an error in this case because the rule definitions are in *conflict*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The value produced by `max_memory` cannot be 32 and 4 **at the same time**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In some cases, having an undefined result for a document is not desirable.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In those cases, policies can use the `default` keyword to provide a fallback value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] As a shorthand for defining nested rule structures, it's valid to use references as rule heads.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Any term, except the very first, in a rule head's reference can be a variable.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] These variables can be assigned within the rule, just as for any other partial rule, to dynamically construct a nested collection of objects.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The first variable declared in a rule head's reference divides the reference in a leading constant portion and a trailing dynamic portion.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Other rules are allowed to overlap with the dynamic portion (dynamic extent) without causing a compile-time conflict.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In the above example, rule `R2` overlaps with the dynamic portion of rule `R1`'s reference (`[x].r`), which is allowed at compile-time, as these rules aren't guaranteed to produce conflicting output.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] However, as `R1` defines `x` as `"q"` and `y` as `1`, a conflict will be reported at evaluation-time.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Conflicts are detected at compile-time, where possible, between rules even if they are within the dynamic extent of another rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Above, `R2` and `R3` are within the dynamic extent of `R1`, but are in conflict with each other, which is detected at compile-time (note the `rego_type_error`, rather than `eval_conflict_error` seen above).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In the above example, `R1` is within the dynamic extent of `R2` and a conflict cannot be detected at compile-time.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] However, at evaluation-time `R2` will attempt to inject a value under key `t` in an object value defined by `R1`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This is a conflict, as rules are not allowed to modify or replace values defined by other rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego supports user-defined functions that can be called with the same semantics as built-in functions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] They have access to both the data document and the input document.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For example, the following function will return the result of trimming the spaces from a string and then splitting it by periods.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Functions may have an arbitrary number of inputs, but exactly one output.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Function arguments may be any kind of term.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If you need multiple outputs, write your functions so that the output is an array, object or set containing your results.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If the output term is omitted, it is equivalent to having the output term be the literal `true`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Furthermore, `if` can be used to write shorter definitions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The outputs of user functions have some additional limitations, namely that they must resolve to a single value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] A given function call will execute all functions that match the signature given.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] On the other hand, if a call matches no functions, then the result is undefined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego does not support the overloading of functions by the number of parameters.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If two function definitions are given with the same function name but different numbers of parameters, a compile-time type error is generated.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In the unusual case that it is critical to use the same name, the function could be made to take the list of parameters as a single array.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] However, this approach is not generally recommended because it sacrifices some helpful compile-time checking and can be quite error-prone.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Users are recommended to use the `future.keywords.not` import whenever using the `not` keyword, as it fixes a long-standing semantic issue with negation in Rego.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Read more about it in the Improved Negation Semantics section of the `not` keyword overview.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] To generate the content of a virtual document, OPA attempts to bind variables in the body of the rule such that all expressions in the rule evaluate to True.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This generates the correct result when the expressions represent assertions about what states should exist in the data stored in OPA.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In some cases, you want to express that certain states *should not* exist in the data stored in OPA.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For safety, a variable appearing in a negated expression must also appear in another non-negated equality expression in the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Negation is required to check whether some value *does not* exist in a collection: `not p["foo"]`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] That is not the same as complementing the `==` operator in an expression `p[_] == "foo"` which yields `p[_] != "foo"` which means for any item in `p`, return true if the item is not `"foo"`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] See more details in the Regal documentation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Logical OR/AND in Rego is structured differently from other languages you might be familiar with.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] See the notes here on logical OR or here for logical AND for more details.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Have a look at the other examples for `not` in the examples section to learn more about using this keyword.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Rego allows for several ways to express universal quantification.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The query will be satisfied **if there is an `i`** such that the query's expressions are simultaneously satisfied.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Therefore, there are other ways to express the desired policy.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For this policy, you can also define a rule that finds if there exists a bitcoin-mining app (which is easy using the `some` keyword).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] And then you use negation to check that there is NO bitcoin-mining app.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Technically, you're using a negation and an existential quantifier, which is logically the same as a universal quantifier.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The `undefined` result above is expected because no default value was defined for `no_bitcoin_miners_using_negation`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Since the body of the rule fails to match, there is no value generated.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The reason the rule is incorrect is that variables in Rego are *existentially quantified*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] This means that rule bodies and queries express FOR ANY and not FOR ALL.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] To express FOR ALL in Rego complement the logic in the rule body (e.g., `!=` becomes `==`) and then complement the check using negation (e.g., `no_bitcoin_miners` becomes `not any_bitcoin_miners`).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Alternatively, the same kind of logic can be implemented inside a single rule using comprehensions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Whether you use negation, comprehensions, or `every` to express FOR ALL is up to you.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The `every` keyword should lend itself nicely to a rule formulation that closely follows how requirements are stated, and thus enhances your policy's readability.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The comprehension version is more concise than the negation variant, and does not require a helper rule while the negation version is more verbose but a bit simpler and allows for more complex ORs.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Have a look at the other examples for `some` and `every` in the examples section.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] In Rego, policies are defined inside *modules*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Modules are typically represented in Unicode text and encoded in UTF-8.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Comments begin with the `#` character and continue until the end of the line.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Packages group the rules defined in one or more modules into a particular namespace.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Because rules are namespaced they can be safely shared across projects.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Modules contributing to the same package do not have to be located in the same directory.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The rules defined in a module are automatically exported.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] That is, they can be queried under OPA’s Data API provided the appropriate package is given.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Valid package names are variables or references that only contain string operands.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For more details see the language grammar.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Import statements declare dependencies that modules have on documents defined outside the package.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] By importing a document, the identifiers exported by that document can be referenced within the current module.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] All modules contain implicit statements which import the `data` and `input` documents.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Modules use the same syntax to declare dependencies on base and virtual documents.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Similarly, modules can declare dependencies on query arguments by specifying an import path that starts with `input`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The `some` keyword allows queries to explicitly declare local variables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Use the `some` keyword in rules that contain unification statements or references with variable operands **if** variables contained in those statements are not declared using `:=` .
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For example, the following rule generates tuples of array indices for servers in the "west" region that contain "db" in their name.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The first element in the tuple is the site index and the second element is the server index.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Querying for the tuples returns two results.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Without declaring `i` with the `some` keyword, introducing the `i` rule above would have changed the result of `tuples` because the `i` symbol in the body would capture the global value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Try removing `some i, j` and see what happens!
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The `some` keyword is not required but it's recommended to avoid situations like the one above where introduction of a rule inside a package could change behaviour of other rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] For using the `some` keyword with iteration, see the documentation of the `in` operator.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The `every` keyword takes an (optional) key argument, a value argument, a domain, and a block of further queries, its "body".
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] The keyword is used to explicitly assert that its body is true for *any element in the domain*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] It will iterate over the domain, bind its variables, and check that the body holds for those bindings.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If one of the bindings does not yield a successful evaluation of the body, the overall statement is undefined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If the domain is empty, the overall statement is true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] Evaluating `every` does **not** introduce new bindings into the rule evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p01] If you need to express `not every x in xs { p(x) }` please use `some x in xs; not p(x)` instead.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `with` keyword allows queries to programmatically specify values nested under the input document or the data document, or built-in functions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] It's also possible to use `with` multiple times in the same query.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] `dev` role allows `GET`, even for an unknown user in the policy.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Catherine is only allowed access at weekends.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `with` keyword acts as a modifier on expressions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] A single expression is allowed to have zero or more `with` modifiers.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `<target>`s must be references to values in the input document (or the input document itself) or data document, or references to functions (built-in or not).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When applied to the `data` document, the `<target>` must not attempt to partially define virtual documents.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] For example, given a virtual document at path `data.foo.bar`, the compiler will generate an error if the policy attempts to replace `data.foo.bar.baz`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `with` keyword only affects the attached expression.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Subsequent expressions will see the unmodified value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] 4. a reference to a rule that will be used as the *value*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When the replacement value is a function, its arity needs to match the replaced function's arity; and the types must be compatible.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Replacement functions can call the function they're replacing **without causing recursion**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Note that function replacement via `with` does not affect the evaluation of the function arguments: if running `f(input.x), and`input.x`is undefined, the replacement of`concat` does not change the result of the evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `default` keyword allows policies to define a default value for documents produced by rules with complete definitions.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The default value is used when all the rules sharing the same name are undefined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Without the default definition, the `allow` document would be undefined for the same input.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The term may be any scalar, composite, or comprehension value but it may not be a variable or reference.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If the value is a composite then it may not contain variables or references.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Comprehensions however may, as the result of a comprehension is never undefined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Similar to rules, the `default` keyword can be applied to functions as well.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When `clamp_positive` is queried, the return value will be either the argument provided to the function or `0`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The value of a `default` function follows the same conditions as that of a `default` rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] A `default` function will still fail (as in not evaluate, even to the default value) if any of the arguments provided in the call are **undefined**.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The reason for this is that the arguments are evaluated before the function is even called, and an undefined argument halts evaluation at that point.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Have a look at the other examples for `default` in the examples section to learn more.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `else` keyword is a basic control flow construct that gives you control over rule evaluation order.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Rules grouped together with the `else` keyword are evaluated until a match is found.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Once a match is found, rule evaluation does not proceed to rules further in the chain.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `else` keyword is useful if you are porting policies into Rego from an order-sensitive system like iptables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] In the example below, evaluation stops immediately after the first rule even though the input matches the second rule as well.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] In the next example, the input matches the second rule (but not the first) so evaluation continues to the second rule before stopping.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `else` keyword may be used repeatedly on the same rule and there is no limit imposed on the number of `else` clauses on a rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] However, it is recommended that policy authors use the `else` keyword sparingly to avoid tightly coupled rules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The membership operator `in` lets you check if an element is part of a collection (array, set, or object).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] A "non-ground value" is a value that contains variables - like `{"foo": y}` where `y` is a variable that gets bound during evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] This is the opposite of a "ground value" which contains no variables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] For a formal definition, see ground term.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The assignment operator `:=` is used to assign values to variables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Variables assigned inside a rule are locally scoped to that rule and shadow global variables.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Assigned variables are not allowed to appear before the assignment in the query.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Rego supports two kinds of equality: comparison (`==`) and unification `=`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Generally, to test equality, using `==` for the comparison is recommended.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The unification operator `=` can be thought of as a combination of `:=` and `==`, and is generally suited to some more advanced use cases.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Comparison checks if two values are equal within a rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If the left or right hand side contains a variable that has not been assigned a value, the compiler throws an error.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Values used in comparison must be assigned before the comparison is made.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Unification (`=`) combines assignment and comparison.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Rego will assign variables to values that make the comparison true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Unification lets you ask for values for variables that make an expression true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] As opposed to when assignment (`:=`) is used, the order of expressions in a rule does not affect the document’s content.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Best practice is to use assignment `:=` and comparison `==` unless you know you need to use unification.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The additional compiler checks help avoid errors when writing policy, and the additional syntax helps make the intent clearer when reading policy.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Under the hood `:=` and `==` are syntactic sugar for `=`, local variable creation, and additional compiler checks.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] None of these operators bind variables contained in the expression.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] As a result, if either operand is a variable, the variable must appear in another expression in the same rule that would cause the variable to be bound, i.e., an equality expression or the target position of a built-in function.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] In some cases, rules must perform simple arithmetic, aggregation, and so on.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Rego provides a number of built-in functions (or “built-ins”) for performing these tasks.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Built-ins can be easily recognized by their syntax.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Built-ins usually take one or more input values and produce one output value.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Unless stated otherwise, all built-ins accept values or variables as output arguments.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If a built-in function is invoked with a variable as input, the variable must be *safe*, i.e., it must be assigned elsewhere in the query.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Built-ins can include "." characters in the name.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If you are adding custom built-ins to OPA, consider namespacing them to avoid naming conflicts, e.g., `org.example.special_func`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] See the Policy Reference document for details on each built-in function.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] By default, built-in function calls that encounter runtime errors evaluate to undefined (which can usually be treated as `false`) and do not halt policy evaluation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] This ensures that built-in functions can be called with invalid inputs without causing the entire policy to stop evaluating.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] In most cases, policies do not have to implement any kind of error handling logic.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If error handling is required, the built-in function call can be negated to test for undefined.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The package and individual rules in a module can be annotated with a rich set of metadata.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Annotations are grouped within a *metadata block*, and must be specified as YAML within a comment block that **must** start with `# METADATA`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Also, every line in the comment block containing the annotation **must** start at Column 1 in the module/file, or otherwise, they will be ignored.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] OPA will attempt to parse the YAML document in comments following the initial `# METADATA` comment.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If the YAML document cannot be parsed, OPA will return an error.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If you need to include additional comments between the comment block and the next statement, include a blank line immediately after the comment block containing the YAML document.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Annotations can be defined at the rule or package level.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `scope` annotation in a metadata block determines how that metadata block will be applied.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If the `scope` field is omitted, it defaults to the scope for the statement that immediately follows the annotation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Since the `document` scope annotation applies to all rules with the same name in the same package and the `package` and `subpackages` scope annotations apply to all packages with a matching path, metadata blocks with these scopes are applied over all files with applicable package- and rule paths.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] As there is no ordering across files in the same package, the `document`, `package`, and `subpackages` scope annotations can only be specified **once** per path.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] An `entrypoint` annotation implies a `scope` of either `package` or `document`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When `entrypoint` is set to `true` on a rule, the `scope` is automatically set to `document` if not explicitly provided.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Setting the `scope` to `rule` will result in an error, as an entrypoint always applies to the whole document.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `labels` annotation is a map of arbitrary key-value pairs attached to a rule (or document, package, or subpackages scope).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When rules with `labels` are successfully evaluated, a merged label map is recorded in decision log events under the `rule_labels` field.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Labels from subpackages-scoped, package-scoped, document-scoped, and rule-scoped annotations are folded into a single map per rule with inner-scope-wins precedence (on conflicting keys, a rule-scope label overrides document, which overrides package, which overrides subpackages).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Identical merged maps across rules are deduplicated.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `title` annotation is a string value giving a human-readable name to the annotation target.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `description` annotation is a string value describing the annotation target, such as its purpose.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `related_resources` annotation is a list of *related-resource* entries, where each links to some related external resource; such as RFCs and other reading material.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] A *related-resource* entry can either be an object or a short-form string holding a single URL.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When a *related-resource* entry is presented as a string, it needs to be a valid URL.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `authors` annotation is a list of author entries, where each entry denotes an *author*.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] An *author* entry can either be an object or a short-form string.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] At least one of the above fields are required for a valid `author` entry.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When an *author* entry is presented as a string, it has the format `{ name } [ "<" email ">"]`; where the name of the author is a sequence of whitespace-separated words.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Optionally, the last word may represent an email, if enclosed with `<>`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `organizations` annotation is a list of string values representing the organizations associated with the annotation target.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `schemas` annotation is a list of key value pairs, associating schemas to data values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] In-depth information on this topic can be found in the Annotations section.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Schema files can be referenced by path, where each path starts with the `schema` namespace, and trailing components specify the path of the schema file (sans file-ending) relative to the root directory specified by the `--schema` flag on applicable commands.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If the `--schema` flag is not present, referenced schemas are ignored during type checking.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Schema definitions can be inlined by specifying the schema structure as a YAML or JSON map.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Inlined schemas are always used to inform type checking for the `eval`, `check`, and `test` commands; in contrast to by-reference schema annotations, which require the `--schema` flag to be present in order to be evaluated.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `entrypoint` annotation is a boolean used to mark rules and packages that should be used as entrypoints for a policy.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] This value is false by default, and can only be used at `document` or `package` scope.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] When used on a rule with no explicit `scope` set, the presence of an `entrypoint` annotation will automatically set the scope to `document`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `build` and `eval` CLI commands will automatically pick up annotated entrypoints; you do not have to specify them with `--entrypoint`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Unless the `--prune-unused` flag is used, any rule transitively referring to a package or rule declared as an entrypoint will also be enumerated as an entrypoint.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `custom` annotation is a mapping of user-defined data, mapping string keys to arbitrarily typed values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Information in metadata blocks can be accessed in a number of ways.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] In the example below, you can see how to access an annotation from within a policy.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The following policy uses the `rego.metadata.rule()` function to access the metadata from the rule to show in the output message.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] If you'd like more examples and information on this, you can see more here under the Rego policy reference.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `ast.AnnotationSet` is a collection of all `ast.Annotations` declared in a set of modules.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The `ast.AnnotationSet` can be flattened into a slice of `ast.AnnotationsRef`, which is a complete, sorted list of all annotations, grouped by the path and location of their targeted package or -rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] Given an `ast.Rule`, the `ast.AnnotationSet` can return the chain of annotations declared for that rule, and its path ancestry.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p02] The returned slice is ordered starting with the annotations for the rule, going outward to the farthest node with declared annotations in the rule's path ancestry.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] You can provide one or more input schema files and/or data schema files to `opa eval` to improve static type checking and get more precise error reports as you develop Rego code.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Schemas can be provided to OPA in two main ways: by supplying external JSON Schema files using the `-s` command-line flag (explained below), or by embedding schema definitions directly within your Rego files using schema annotations (detailed further down in this document).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Both methods help improve static type checking.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The `-s` flag can be used to upload schemas for input and data documents in JSON Schema format.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] You can either load a single JSON schema file for the input document or directory of schema files.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] When a single file is passed, it is a schema file associated with the input document globally.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This means that for all rules in all packages, the `input` has a type derived from that schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] There is no constraint on the name of the file, it could be anything.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] When a directory path is passed, annotations will be used in the code to indicate what expressions map to what schemas (see below).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Both input schema files and data schema files can be provided in the same directory, with different names.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The directory of schemas may have any sub-directories.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Notice that when a directory is passed the input document does not have a schema associated with it globally.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This must also be indicated via an annotation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Samples provided at: `github.com/aavarghese/opa-schema-examples`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Consider the following Rego code, which assumes as input a Kubernetes admission review.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] For resources that are Pods, it checks that the image name starts with a specific prefix.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Notice that this code has a typo in it: `input.request.kind.kinds` is undefined and should have been `input.request.kind.kind`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Clearly there are 2 image names that are in violation of the policy.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The empty value returned is indistinguishable from a situation where the input did not violate the policy.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This error is therefore causing the policy not to catch violating inputs appropriately.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] With this feature, it is possible to pass a schema to `opa eval`, written in JSON Schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Consider the admission review schema provided at `schemas/input.json`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This indicates the error to the Rego developer right away, without having the need to observe the results of runs on actual data, thereby improving productivity.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] See the annotations documentation for general information relating to annotations.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The `schemas` field specifies an array associating schemas to data values.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The type checker derives a Rego Object type for the schema and an appropriate entry is added to the type environment before type checking the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This entry is removed upon exit from the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In the first `allow` rule above, the input document has the schema `input.json`, and `data.acl` has the schema `acl-schema.json`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Note that the relative path inside the `mySchemasDir` directory identifies a schema, omitting the `.json` suffix, and uses the global variable `schema` to stand for the top-level of the directory.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Schemas in annotations are proper Rego references.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] So `schema.input` is also valid, but `schema.acl-schema` is not.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The expression `data.acl.foo` in this rule would result in a type error because the schema contained in `acl-schema.json` only defines object properties `"alice"` and `"bob"` in the ACL data document.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] On the other hand, this annotation does not constrain other paths under `data`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] What it says is that the type of `data.acl` is known statically, but not that of other paths.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] So for example, `data.foo` is not a type error and gets assigned the type `Any`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Note that the second `allow` rule doesn't have a METADATA comment block attached to it, and hence will not be type checked with any schemas.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] On a different note, schema annotations can also be added to policy files part of a bundle package loaded via `opa eval --bundle` along with the `--schema` parameter for type checking a set of `*.rego` policy files.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The following sections explain how the different scopes affect `schema` annotation overriding for type checking.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In the example above, the second rule does not include an annotation so type checking of the second rule would not take schemas into account.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In this example, the annotation with `document` scope has the same affect as the two `rule` scoped annotations in the previous example.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] `package` scoped schema annotations are useful when all rules in the same package operate on the same input structure.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In some cases, when policies are organized into many sub-packages, it is useful to declare schemas recursively for them using the `subpackages` scope.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This snippet would declare the top-level schema for `input` for the `kubernetes.admission` package as well as all subpackages.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] If admission control rules were defined inside packages like `kubernetes.admission.workloads.pods`, they would be able to pick up that one schema declaration.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] JSON Schemas are often incomplete specifications of the format of data.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] For example, a Kubernetes Admission Review resource has a field `object` which can contain any other Kubernetes resource.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] A schema for Admission Review has a generic type `object` for that field that has no further specification.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] To allow more precise type checking in such cases, schema overriding is supported.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In this example, the `input` is associated with an Admission Review schema, and furthermore `input.request.object` is set to have the schema of a Kubernetes Pod.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In effect, the second schema annotation overrides the first one.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Overriding is a schema transformation feature and combines existing schemas.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In this case, the Admission Review schema is combined with that of a Pod.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Notice that the order of schema annotations matter for overriding to work correctly.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Given a schema annotation, if a prefix of the path already has a type in the environment, then the annotation has the effect of merging and overriding the existing type with the type derived from the schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In the example above, the prefix `input` already has a type in the type environment, so the second annotation overrides this existing type.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Overriding affects the type of the longest prefix that already has a type.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] If no such prefix exists, the new path and type are added to the type environment for the scope of the rule.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Notice that `b` still has its fields `c` and `d`, so overriding has a merging effect as well.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Moreover, the type of expression `a.b.e` is now `E1` instead of `E`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Overriding can also add new paths to an existing type.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Schemas enhance the type checking capability of OPA, and are not used to validate the input and data documents against desired schemas.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This burden is still on the user and care must be taken when using overriding to ensure that the input and data provided are sensible and validated against the transformed schemas.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] It is sometimes useful to have different input schemas for different rules in the same package.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In this example, the schema `input.json` is associated with the input document in the rule `allow`, and the schema `whocan-input-schema.json` with the input document for the rule `whocan`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Rego has a gradual type system meaning that types can be partially known statically.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] For example, an object could have certain fields whose types are known and others that are unknown statically.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] OPA type checks what it knows statically and leaves the unknown parts to be type checked at runtime.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] An OPA object type has two parts: the static part with the type information known statically, and a dynamic part, which can be nil (meaning everything is known statically) or non-nil and indicating what is unknown.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] When deriving a type from a schema, the compiler tries to match what is known and unknown in the schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] For example, an `object` that has no specified fields becomes the Rego type `Object{Any: Any}`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] However, currently `additionalProperties` and `additionalItems` are ignored.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] When a schema is fully specified, the dynamic part is set to nil, meaning that a strict interpretation is used in order to get the most out of static type checking.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This is the case even if `additionalProperties` is set to `true` in the schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In the future, this feature will be taken into account when deriving Rego types.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] When overriding existing types, the dynamicity of the overridden prefix is preserved.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] JSON Schema provides keywords such as `anyOf` and `allOf` to structure a complex schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] For `anyOf`, at least one of the subschemas must be true, and for `allOf`, all subschemas must be true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The type checker is able to identify such keywords and derive a more robust Rego type through more complex schemas.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Specifically, `anyOf` acts as an Rego Or type where at least one (can be more than one) of the subschemas is true.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The type checker finds the first error in the Rego code, suggesting that `servers` should be either `kind` or `server`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Once this is fixed, the second typo is highlighted, prompting the user to choose between `accessNum` and `version`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Specifically, `allOf` keyword implies that all conditions under `allOf` within a schema must be met by the given data.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] `allOf` is implemented through merging the types from all of the JSON subSchemas listed under `allOf` before parsing the result to convert it to a Rego type.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Merging of the JSON subSchemas essentially combines the passed in subSchemas based on what types they contain.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The type checker finds the first error in the Rego code, suggesting that `servers` should be `server`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Once this is fixed, the second typo is highlighted, informing the user that `versions` should be one of `accessNum` or `version`.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Because the properties `kind`, `version`, and `accessNum` are all under the `allOf` keyword, the resulting schema that the given data must be validated against will contain the types contained in these properties children (string and integer).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] OPA's type checker will fetch these remote references by default.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] To control the remote hosts schemas will be fetched from, pass a capabilities file to your `opa eval` or `opa check` call.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Starting from the capabilities.json of your OPA version (which can be found in the repository), add an `allow_net` key to it: its values are the IP addresses or host names that OPA is supposed to connect to for retrieving remote schemas.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Currently this feature admits schemas written in JSON Schema but does not support every feature available in this format.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] A note of caution: overriding is a flexible capability that must be used carefully.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] In this case, the root of all documents is being overridden to have some schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Since all Rego code lives under `data` as virtual documents, this in practice renders all of them inaccessible (resulting in type errors).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Similarly, assigning a schema to a package name is not a good idea and can cause problems.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Care must also be taken when defining overrides so that the transformation of schemas is sensible and data can be validated against the transformed schema.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] For more examples, please see the opa-schema-examples repository.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] This contains samples for Envoy, Kubernetes, and Terraform including corresponding JSON Schemas.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] For a tool that generates JSON Schema from JSON samples, please see here (Other Tools).
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] The Rego compiler supports `strict mode`, where additional constraints and safety checks are enforced during compilation.
[src:rego-opa-policy/policy-language-p03] Compiler Strict mode is supported by the `check` command, and can be enabled through the `--strict`/`-S` flag.
